# ‚≠ê PART‚Äì2: HOW TO WRITE CONNECTOR JSON **BY YOURSELF** (WITHOUT AI)

It's simple once you understand **6 rules**.

---

# ‚úî RULE 1 ‚Äî Connector name

```
"name": "<anything-you-want>"
```

---

# ‚úî RULE 2 ‚Äî connector.class

This tells Debezium *what database you are using*.

Use this table:

| Database   | connector.class                                      |
| ---------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| PostgreSQL | `io.debezium.connector.postgresql.PostgresConnector` |
| MySQL      | `io.debezium.connector.mysql.MySqlConnector`         |
| MongoDB    | `io.debezium.connector.mongodb.MongoDbConnector`     |
| SQL Server | `io.debezium.connector.sqlserver.SqlServerConnector` |
| Oracle     | `io.debezium.connector.oracle.OracleConnector`       |

Just change this only.

---

# ‚úî RULE 3 ‚Äî Database connection fields

Every DB has these:

```
database.hostname
database.port
database.user
database.password
database.dbname (or names)
```

---

# ‚úî RULE 4 ‚Äî database.server.name

This is the **Kafka topic prefix**.

You choose any name.

Example:

```
"database.server.name": "inventory"
```

Kafka topics will be:

```
inventory.public.users
inventory.public.orders
```

---

# ‚úî RULE 5 ‚Äî table.include.list

Pick which tables to monitor.

```
"table.include.list": "schema.table1,schema.table2"
```

or ALL:

```
"table.include.list": "public.*"
```

---

# ‚úî RULE 6 ‚Äî Kafka history topic

```
"database.history.kafka.bootstrap.servers": "kafka:9092"
"database.history.kafka.topic": "schema-changes.<prefix>"
```

---

# ‚≠ê PART‚Äì3: HOW TO WRITE REGISTRY CONNECTOR COMMAND BY YOURSELF

REGISTRATION COMMAND FORMAT:

---

## üî• POST command to create a connector

**Template:**

```
curl -X POST http://localhost:8083/connectors \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @<file-name>
```

**Example:**

```
curl -X POST http://localhost:8083/connectors \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @postgres-connector.json
```

---

## üî• Update existing connector

```
curl -X PUT http://localhost:8083/connectors/postgres-connector/config \
-H "Content-Type: application/json" \
--data @postgres-connector.json
```

---

## üî• List connectors

```
curl http://localhost:8083/connectors
```

---

## üî• Check a connector status

```
curl http://localhost:8083/connectors/postgres-connector/status
```

---

## üî• Delete a connector

```
curl -X DELETE http://localhost:8083/connectors/postgres-connector
```

---

# ‚≠ê PART‚Äì4: HOW TO BUILD THE REGISTRY COMMAND YOURSELF

### üéØ Only 3 things change:

1. **Verb** (`POST` or `PUT`)
2. **Port** (`8083`)
3. **File name**

You can create ANY connector using this pattern:

```
curl -X POST http://<connect-host>:8083/connectors \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @<your-file.json>
```

---

# ‚≠ê PART‚Äì5: AI PROMPT TO GENERATE CONNECTOR JSON FOR ANY DATABASE

Use this:

