=========================================================================what if our.json file in some folder ======================================================================







Great question ‚Äî and VERY important for real DevOps work.

If your connector JSON file is inside **any folder**, like:

```
connectors/postgres-connector.json
```

Then your curl command becomes:

---

# ‚úÖ **Correct curl command with folder path**

```
curl -X POST http://localhost:8083/connectors \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @connectors/postgres-connector.json
```

That‚Äôs it.

---

# üî• **RULE:**

Whatever the **relative or absolute path** of the file is,
you must put the SAME path after `@`

---

# ‚≠ê Examples (you will use these again and again)

### 1Ô∏è‚É£ File inside a folder

```
--data @connectors/postgres-connector.json
```

### 2Ô∏è‚É£ File inside nested folders

```
--data @config/connectors/postgres/postgres-connector.json
```

### 3Ô∏è‚É£ File in parent directory

```
--data @../postgres-connector.json
```

### 4Ô∏è‚É£ Absolute path

```
--data @/home/ubuntu/debezium/connectors/postgres-connector.json
```

### 5Ô∏è‚É£ Path with spaces (rare)

```
--data @"connectors/my connectors/postgres-connector.json"
```

---

# ‚ö†Ô∏è IMPORTANT

You must run the curl command **from the same machine** where the JSON file exists.

If the JSON is inside your **Debezium container**, you must:

```
docker exec -it debezium bash
```

Then:

```
curl -X POST http://localhost:8083/connectors \
 -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
 --data @connectors/postgres-connector.json
```

---

# ‚≠ê TIP: How to check file path quickly

Run:

```
ls connectors/
```

If you see:

```
postgres-connector.json
```

Then your path is correct.

---

# ‚≠ê YOUR FINAL VERSION (copy-paste)

```
curl -X POST http://localhost:8083/connectors \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data @connectors/postgres-connector.json
```

