I will tell you exactly whether to use POST or PUT.
==========================================================================clear explanation=========================================
Not exactly ‚Äî let me correct it **clearly and accurately**:

# ‚ùå Wrong understanding:

> ‚ÄúIf connector container is created ‚áí use PUT
> Otherwise ‚áí use POST‚Äù

This is **not correct**.

---

# ‚úÖ Correct understanding (VERY IMPORTANT)

You choose **POST or PUT based ONLY on whether the connector ALREADY EXISTS inside Kafka Connect**, NOT based on the container.

Kafka Connect runs inside the Debezium container, but:

### ‚úî The container may be running

### ‚ùå But the connector might not exist

A connector is like a ‚Äújob‚Äù or ‚Äúconfiguration‚Äù stored inside Kafka Connect ‚Äî NOT the container.

---

# ‚≠ê REAL RULE (easy and correct)

## üîµ **POST = Connector does NOT exist yet**

Use POST only when you are **creating** the connector for the first time.

Example:

```
curl -X POST http://localhost:8083/connectors \
 -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
 --data @postgres.json
```

---

## üîµ **PUT = Connector already exists**

Use PUT only when you want to **modify or update** an existing connector.

Example:

```
curl -X PUT http://localhost:8083/connectors/postgres-connector/config \
 -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
 --data @postgres.json
```

---

# ‚≠ê So the REAL formula is:

### üëâ Connector exists ‚Üí **PUT**

### üëâ Connector does not exist ‚Üí **POST**

NOT based on container running.

---

# ‚≠ê How to confirm if connector exists?

Run:

```
curl http://localhost:8083/connectors
```

You will see something like:

```
["postgres-connector"]
```

If your connector name appears ‚Üí **use PUT**

If blank list:

```
[]
```

‚Üí **use POST**

---

# ‚≠ê SIMPLEST WAY TO REMEMBER

| Situation                     | Use      |
| ----------------------------- | -------- |
| First time creating connector | **POST** |
| Changing config / updating    | **PUT**  |
| Recreate after deleting       | **POST** |
| Fixing wrong tables/password  | **PUT**  |

---

# ‚≠ê Why do we not use POST again for an existing connector?

Because POST will give this error:

```
409 Conflict: Connector already exists
```

Kafka Connect does not allow duplicate connector names.

---

# üéØ FINAL ANSWER TO YOUR QUESTION:

> **‚ÄúIf connector container is created ‚Äî use PUT?‚Äù**

‚ùå No.
Even if Debezium container is running, you still must check whether the **connector configuration exists**.

Use:

### ‚úî POST if the connector is not registered

### ‚úî PUT if the connector is already registered

---

